<font color="#FF0000">HELLO AGAIN!</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep 22  2:56:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hello Again Fellows:<br><br>
Just when I felt that this discussion was going straight into a nosedive and ready to &quot;crash and burn,&quot; you surprise me and began speaking of substancive topics.  PSTD is a topic that has needed airing for awhile.  At one point, we had a bit of discussion on it, but it didn't get too far.<br><br>
I do not believe from the discussions so far that I have this problem, but that doesn't mean that Vietnam hasn't effected me too.  I don't think anyone could come through that experience without some changed perspectives.  <br><br>
Above, someone said that &quot;we are the sum of the parts...&quot; or something close.  I'd like to point out that this is not necessarily true.  There are many different responses to stresses.  Could it be much the same as the response to toxic chemicals?  <br><br>
When exposed to chemicals, there are many different responses that the body can take, and there are recognized properties of certain chemicals.  For instance, the effects of chemical exposures could be additive (where the sum of the effects of the chemicals are equal to the effects of each chemical if applied separately and added together, or 2 + 3 = 5).  This is what was mentioned above about us being the sum of our experiences.  <br><br>
But there are other interactions, which may relate to how we handle psychological stress too.  Synergistic effects of chemicals mean that together the effects of the chemical are not the sum of its parts, but much greater when given together (2 + 3 = 20).  Could it be the same with experiences?  Could the effects of certain experiences, under certain conditions, have a much greater effect than would normally have been experienced?<br><br>
There are also, for chemical exposures, effects called by toxicologists as &quot;potentiation&quot; and &quot;antagonism.&quot;  In these cases the chemical can have no effect on a person, but can &quot;potentiate&quot; another chemical to have a much greater than normal effect (0 + 2 = 10).  Or a chemical with desirable effects can be interferred with by another chemical.  Is it possible that some people did not develop PSTD because of an &quot;antagonistic&quot; experience?  Is it possible that the Marine Corps training or the Survival School training aircrews received &quot;innoculated&quot; them and served as a protective factor?<br><br>
These are basic concepts in toxicology, but I haven't seen whether thare is an equivalent situation in the psychology of people.  If so, then it could provide an insight as to why some people get PSTD and some do not.<br><br>
I mentioned that Vietnam did change me a bit.  I found that I didn't have as much tolerence to normal organizational BS, and tended to call people on it when perhaps I should have kept my mouth shut.  I think that this probably resulted from my Vietnam experience.  <br><br>
Yes, unquestionably in my mind, we could have won that war!  We needed only to make the decision to do so.  But four Presidents (Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon and Ford) decided that we shouldn't try for a win.  I have used the analogy elsewhere here that it was like playing a football game, having to abide by all the rules of football, while telling the other team that there were no rules.  The other team could use the out-of-bounds (in this case, Cmabodia, Laos and Thailang) for their passing game while we had to stay in bounds.  The other team could sit in our huddle to learn of our next play, and could play any number of players.  The other team could go to our rooting section, and replace it with theirs.  They could even use more than one football!  How can anyone win a game like that?  <br><br>
There was a plan for an invasion of the North by US forces, which would probably have ended the war, in 1970-71.  The publicity surrounding the &quot;unsuccessful&quot; raid on San Tai scuttled the plan.  But, in my mind, we could have done it and been through with the war.  But politics determined the day.  Hence, I have an abiding distrust of politicians.
